    <statement><p>Solve the equation.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ {\frac{5}{2a}+\frac{3}{4a}}={-4}  }</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="31" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left\{\frac{-13}{16}\right\}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To clear fractions in an equation, multiply each side of the equation by a common denominator. For this problem, a common denominator is <m>{8a}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
  {\frac{5}{2a}+\frac{3}{4a}} \amp = {-4} \\
  {\frac{5}{2a}\cdot 8a+\frac{3}{4a}\cdot 8a} \amp = {-4\cdot 8a} \\
  20+6 \amp = {-32a} \\
  26 \amp = {-32a} \\
  \frac{26}{-32} \amp = \frac{{-32a}}{-32} \\
  {\left\{\frac{-13}{16}\right\}} \amp = a \\
  a \amp  = {\left\{\frac{-13}{16}\right\}}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>We must check solutions when we solve rational equations. By the original equation, the domain condition is <m>a \ne 0</m>. This doesn<rsq/>t conflict with the solution above, so the solution is <m>a = {\left\{\frac{-13}{16}\right\}}</m>.</p>
</solution>
